ENet 1.3.18 uses one C99 construct (declarations inside `for` initializers) in
enet_protocol_send_outgoing_commands(). The VC++ 2010 (v100) C compiler is C89-only
and rejects it. This patch hoists the declarations to the top of the function.

Apply from the repo root after fetching ENet (the vendored source under
third_party/enet/enet/ is git-ignored):

    git apply third_party/enet/patches/0001-enet-c89-for-loops.patch

--- a/third_party/enet/enet/protocol.c
+++ b/third_party/enet/enet/protocol.c
@@ -1606,11 +1606,14 @@ enet_protocol_send_outgoing_commands (ENetHost * host, ENetEvent * event, int ch
     int sentLength = 0;
     size_t shouldCompress = 0;
     ENetList sentUnreliableCommands;
+    /* C89 (VC10) compatibility: declarations hoisted out of the for-init clauses. */
+    int sendPass, continueSending;
+    ENetPeer * currentPeer;
 
     enet_list_clear (& sentUnreliableCommands);
 
-    for (int sendPass = 0, continueSending = 0; sendPass <= continueSending; ++ sendPass)
-    for (ENetPeer * currentPeer = host -> peers;
+    for (sendPass = 0, continueSending = 0; sendPass <= continueSending; ++ sendPass)
+    for (currentPeer = host -> peers;
          currentPeer < & host -> peers [host -> peerCount];
          ++ currentPeer)
     {
